  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">35</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">As we shall explicitly show below, the regime of validity of the final resonance equation [see Eq. (42) below] should be determined with great care in the double limit of small black-hole temperatures and large field masses</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that the double asymptotic limit (19) corresponds to Kerr-Newman black holes in the near-extremal τ ≪ 1 regime, and to resonant field frequencies near the critical frequency ωc [19] for the superradiant amplification phenomenon in the black-hole spacetime</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">37</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">P. M. Morse and H. Feshbach</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Methods of Theoretical Physics New York,)</subfield>
    <subfield code="p">McGraw-Hill</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">1953</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">38</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that the strong inequality (39) corresponds to the regime ̟ ≫ m</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">We shall assume δ &gt; 0 without loss of generality</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">40</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the relation 1 = e-2iπn, where the resonance parameter n is an integer</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">41</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used equation 6.1.23 of [25] to infer the facts that Γ(2iδ)/Γ(-2iδ) = eiφ1 and Γ(1/2-iδ-κ)/Γ(1/2+iδ-κ) = eiφ2, where {φ1, φ2} ∈ relations imply that R ∈ R</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">R. These</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">42</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that the large-mass Mµ ≫ 1 regime (49) corresponds to the asymptotic m ≫ 1 regime. This also implies the strong inequalities δ ≫ 1 and k ≫ 1 [see Eqs. (61) and (63) below]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">43</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the approximated relation [1 + e-2π(k-δ)]1/2iδ = 1 - ie-2π(k-δ) /2δ + O[(e-2π(k-δ) /δ)2] [25] in the asymptotic k - δ ≫ 1 regime [see [42] and Eq. (61) below]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">44</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">T. M. Zouros and D. M. Eardley</subfield>
    <subfield code="s">Annals Phys.,118,139</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">1979</subfield>
    <subfield code="0">145948</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">45</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">As shown in [44], the specific choice (53) for the physical parameters of the composed black-hole-field system maximizes the growth rate of the superradiant instabilities in the eikonal large-mass Mµ ≫ 1 regime</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">46</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that there is a factor 2 missing (probably due to an accidental typo) in the exponent of [44]. This accidental typo was corrected in:</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">A. B. Gaina</subfield>
    <subfield code="s">Sov.Astron.Lett.,15,243</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">1989</subfield>
    <subfield code="0">277596</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">46</subfield>
    <subfield code="h">A. Arvanitaki and S. Dubovsky</subfield>
    <subfield code="s">Phys.Rev.,D83,044026</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">2011</subfield>
    <subfield code="0">852575</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">47</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Here we have assumed the equality l = m for the harmonic indices of the explosive scalar field, a choice which minimizes the value of K [28] and thus maximizes the value of the exponent δ - k of (52) [see Eq. (22)]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">48</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">It is worth emphasizing again that we assume the relation ωR ≃ ωc [see Eqs. (40) and (43)]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">49</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that, in the eikonal large-mass Mµ ≫ 1 regime (which also corresponds to the m ≫ 1 regime, see [42]), one finds the relation [e-2π(k-δ) /2δ]′ = [e-2π(k-δ) /2δ] × [2π(δ - k)′ - δ′ /δ] = [πe-2π(k-δ) /δ] × (δ - k)′ [1 + O(m-1 )], where here a prime denotes a derivative with respect to the dimensionless variable γ. Thus, in the eikonal large-mass Mµ ≫ 1 regime, the location of the maximum of δ - k corresponds [up to a small correction factor 1+ O(m-1 )] to the location of the maximum of e-2π(k-δ) /2δ [see Eq. (52)]</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">50</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note that the exponent of (52) is characterized by the inequality 2π(δ - k) &lt; 0 in the entire range s ∈ (0, 1] of the dimensionless black-hole rotation parameter (see also [43])</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">51</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">It is worth emphasizing that, in the small frequency Mω ≪ 1 and small charge-coupling qQ ≪ 1 regime, Furuhashi and Nambu [16] have interestingly found that ωI is a monotonically decreasing function of the dimensionless black-hole-field charge coupling parameter qQ [see Eq. (5)]. Intriguingly, in the present study we have proved that the opposite regime of large Mω ≃ Mωc ≫ 1 field frequencies is characterized by a non-monotonic dependence of ωI on the dimensionless black-hole-field charge coupling parameter qQ</subfield>
  </datafield>
